WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.520
 Now let's talk about control structures, logic, loops,

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:04.640
 and all that kind of stuff.

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:06.400
 So the first kind of control structure

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:09.400
 we're gonna deal with is an if statement.

00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:11.440
 And every language has an if statement.

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:13.000
 We have a whole bunch of logical operators

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.520
 that we just got done talking about.

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:17.400
 Equals, the double equals is the question mark.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:21.020
 Triple equals is the same as and same type as.

00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:25.360
 Not equals the not, and then the and and the or.

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:30.000
 The double ampersand is and, and the double vertical bar is or.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.880
 And so triple equals and exclamation double equals,

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:35.880
 and curly braces are the way that we talk about

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:37.720
 the begin and end of the blocks

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:40.200
 that are affected by the if statement.

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:44.720
 So other than that, we say if parent c answer equals 42,

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:46.800
 this is kind of the question that we're gonna ask

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:49.760
 and that's going to lead to a true or a false.

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:53.040
 If it's true, of course the first block is gonna execute,

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:57.000
 and then there's an else, and then if that result is false,

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.720
 the question is false, then the else section

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:01.640
 is gonna execute.

00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:03.720
 And there can be more than one line in here.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:05.960
 I'm just showing one line to keep it small on the screen.

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:10.880
 So when this code all runs, it basically comes in,

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:13.380
 answer is 42, then this is true.

00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:15.240
 Answer equals 42 is true.

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:16.760
 It runs console log hello world,

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:19.480
 then skips the else clause and it's all done.

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:22.800
 So the output of this is indeed hello world.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:28.200
 There's multi-way ifs, and you can hang them together

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:32.340
 just like with else ifs, just like in Python.

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:35.840
 And it does it in order.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:38.320
 If this is false, if the first if is false,

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:41.120
 it checks the else if, and as soon as that's true,

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:44.080
 it runs that block of code and then hops out to the end.

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:48.120
 It doesn't check all of the if questions simultaneously.

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:51.280
 And you can optionally have an else clause

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:54.920
 so that if none of the if else if clauses are true,

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:57.400
 then it just falls through and runs the code

00:01:57.400 --> 00:01:58.860
 in the else block.

00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:02.960
 You can have an indeterminate loop,

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:05.920
 a while loop that runs until something becomes true.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:10.320
 It's a zero trip loop, which means that it runs

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:12.720
 a minimum of zero times, which means it effectively

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.680
 functions the first time through like an if statement.

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:20.040
 So while fuel greater than one, do this thing in the block,

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:22.280
 is really like an if fuel greater than run,

00:02:22.280 --> 00:02:24.980
 if fuel is greater than one, do this block.

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:27.360
 Although in this case, I've built myself an infinite loop

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:29.560
 because fuel starts out at 10, and I say,

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:32.680
 while fuel is greater than one, console.log room,

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:34.720
 which means it's just gonna do that forever,

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:38.240
 and that's because I didn't change the iteration variable,

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:41.040
 in this case fuel, and usually we construct these

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:43.580
 in a way that they terminate eventually.

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:46.620
 And so I've done a much better job in the second one

00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:48.120
 where I set fuel to 10 and I say,

00:02:48.120 --> 00:02:49.860
 while fuel is greater than one,

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:53.320
 and inside the loop I console.log room,

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:56.460
 and then I subtract one, and I go up and up and up and up,

00:02:56.460 --> 00:02:59.500
 and then it's gonna go, and then fuel will eventually

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.960
 get to zero, and then it will exit out the loop and finish.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:04.860
 And so this here is an infinite loop,

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:07.500
 and this is a finite loop.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:08.920
 While loops are always a little tricky

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:11.840
 'cause you've gotta construct the iteration variable

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:14.900
 or make sure you know how to get out of the loop.

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:19.840
 The for loop is a counted loop, and it's going to run,

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:21.040
 and so there's three parts to it,

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:23.280
 and they're separated by semicolons.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:25.840
 It looks really complex, but it's not.

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:27.660
 So you make an iteration variable,

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:29.840
 the first part up to the semicolon

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:33.120
 is the code that runs before the loop starts.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:36.500
 So I'm gonna set this variable count equals one.

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:38.280
 The second part is like a while,

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:40.760
 and it's a top test zero trip loop,

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:43.640
 and as long as count remains less than or equal to six,

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:45.720
 then the body of loop is gonna execute,

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:47.600
 and then each time at the bottom of the loop,

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:48.960
 we're gonna add one.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.640
 So this is gonna go one, two, three, four, five, six.

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:55.040
 When it's equal to six, it's gonna run the sixth time,

00:03:55.040 --> 00:03:56.880
 but then it's gonna come up and be seven,

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:59.040
 but then the loop is not going to run.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.920
 And so that's what's called a counted loop,

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:05.040
 where we have some variable that's just running through

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:06.680
 on a set of numbers.

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:09.800
 In Python, we would use range to do this kind of a thing.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:16.000
 Now, like in Python, we've got the break statement,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.760
 and the break statement just says,

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:20.600
 I'm gonna get out of this loop.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:23.260
 So if this line executes, it looks at the,

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:26.080
 if there's more than one loop, it's the innermost loop,

00:04:26.080 --> 00:04:28.440
 and it just basically escapes the loop

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:30.740
 and moves on to the line of code

00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:33.260
 that follows the loop immediately.

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:36.160
 Just, if it's done, get out.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:37.460
 Don't execute another line.

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:40.800
 It doesn't run that next, the rest of the iteration.

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:44.520
 It just skips out of the loop completely.

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:49.520
 Continue is another very useful thing.

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:54.120
 You can basically say, I wanna give up on this iteration

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:56.720
 and go back up and do the next iteration,

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:58.840
 but the thing is this increment

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:01.400
 usually is this third part of the for loop.

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:03.480
 If you say continue, that actually runs.

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:06.840
 So it actually, continue goes and does the plus plus,

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:08.400
 and then it does the check,

00:05:08.400 --> 00:05:10.680
 and then it either continues to run back here

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:15.040
 or it jumps out if count is now greater than 10,

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:18.040
 and so continue works pretty much the same

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:23.040
 in loops in JavaScript as it does in Python.

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:28.680
 So you can also loop through objects,

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:32.160
 and so here's an object that has three attributes,

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:36.800
 golf, tennis, and ping, and I can say four ball and balls,

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:39.920
 and then that means that this iteration variable

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.940
 is gonna walk through the keys or the attributes.

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:46.200
 So it's gonna be golf, ping, and tennis,

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:48.480
 and then I can use the lookup syntax

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:52.040
 to look up balls sub golf, balls sub tennis,

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.780
 and balls sub ping, and then print all those things out.

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.560
 So that's what's called a definite loop

00:05:56.560 --> 00:06:00.760
 that's looping through an object that we're going to see.

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:02.120
 Now when you're looping through an array,

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:05.320
 which is a linear list, you actually use a counted loop,

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:07.680
 not a definite loop, but objects,

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:09.880
 which are like dictionaries,

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:11.520
 which are like associative arrays,

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:13.960
 we use definite loops to loop through them.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:18.700
 So that is a quick romp through JavaScript,

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:20.120
 not so much to get to the point

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:22.080
 where you can write a bunch of JavaScript,

00:06:22.080 --> 00:06:24.480
 but so you can read it, and then when you get a syntax there,

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:27.000
 hopefully you can fix it.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.580
 (upbeat music)

